04718nam a22007575i 9781501717468DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017174687 a10.7591/97815017174682doi  a(DE-B1597)503532  a(OCoLC)1038479169  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aND212.5.M63W65 2003 7aART0151002bisacsh04a709/.41/09041 aWolff, Janet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAngloModern :bPainting and Modernity in Britain and the United States /cJanet Wolff. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b29 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. AngloModern: The Painting of Modern Life -- t1. Women at the Whitney, 1910–30: Feminism, Sociology, Aesthetics -- t2. Questions of Discovery: The Art of Kathleen McEnery -- t3. Gender and the Haunting of Cities: Or, the Retirement of the Flaneur -- t4. The Feminine in Modern Art: Benjamin, Simmel, and the Gender of Modernity -- t5. The Failure of a Hard Sponge: Class, Ethnicity, and the Art of Mark Gertler -- t6. The "Jewish Mark" in English Painting: Cultural Identity and Modern Art -- tAFTERWORD. Modernism, Realism, Revisionism -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly twentieth-century art and art practice in Britain and the United States were, Janet Wolff asserts, marginalized by critics and historians in very similar ways after the rise of post-Cubist modern art. In a masterly book on the sociology of modernism, Wolff explores work that was primarily realist and figurative and investigates the social, institutional, political, and aesthetic processes by which that art fell by the wayside in the postwar period. Throughout, she shows that questions of gender and ethnicity play an important role in critical, curatorial, and historical evaluations. For example, Wolff finds that the work of the artists central to the development of the Whitney Museum was relegated to a secondary status in the postwar period, when realism was labeled "feminine" in contrast to the aggressive masculinity of abstract expressionism.The three key periods considered in AngloModern are the early twentieth century, when modernist art and existing and new realist traditions coexisted in a certain tension; the postwar period, in which modernism claimed superiority over realism; and the late twentieth century, when a retrieval of the realist and figurative traditions seemed to occur. Wolff concludes by considering this re-emergence, as well as the limitations of earlier discussions of the struggles of realist and figurative art to endure the currents of modernism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEthnicity in art. 0aGender identity in art. 0aModernism (Art)zGreat Britain. 0aModernism (Art)zUnited States. 0aPainting, Americany20th century. 0aPainting, Britishy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aArt History. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171746840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501717468.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK